Why do we even need Distributed Locking?
Imagine your application is running on one server.

        Client
           |
       +---------+
       | Server  |
       +---------+
If two threads access the same object, Java's
	• synchronized 
	• ReentrantLock 
	• Semaphore 
are enough. Because all threads are inside one JVM.

But what happens in Distributed Systems?
At Big companies your application doesn't run on one server.
It may run on

             Load Balancer
           /      |      \
      Server1  Server2  Server3

Each server has
	• its own JVM 
	• its own memory 
	• its own locks 
	
Now imagine

User A
      \
       Server 1
User B
      \
       Server 2
Both try to modify Account #123 at exactly the same time.

Server 1 executes synchronized(account)
Server 2 also executes synchronized(account)
Problem?
These locks are completely different. Each server thinks "I own the lock." Now both update the database.

Result:
Balance becomes incorrect.
Duplicate orders
Duplicate payments
Inventory mismatch
This is called Race Condition

Real World Example
Suppose Flipkart has Only 1 iPhone left, Two customers purchase simultaneously.

Customer A ---> Server1
Customer B ---> Server2

Without distributed locking, Both servers read Stock = 1,
both reduce stock
Stock = 0
Stock = -1
Now company sold 2 phones, Only had 1. Huge business issue.

Solution
We need one lock that every server can understand, Not JVM lock.
A Distributed Lock.

               Lock Server
	              LOCK
                  |
      ----------------------------
      |            |             |
 Server1      Server2      Server3

Only one server gets LOCK SUCCESS, Others wait.

Architecture

                 Client Requests
                        |
                Load Balancer
                        |
      ----------------------------------
      |               |               |
   Service A      Service B      Service C
      |               |               |
      -------Distributed Lock---------
                    |
               Redis / ZooKeeper
                    |
                 Database

Before modifying data, Every service asks

Can I get lock?
If YES Continue.
Otherwise Wait.

Workflow
Suppose
Order #101
needs processing.

Step 1
Server A requests Lock(Order101)
Redis replies Granted

Step 2
Server B also requests Lock(Order101)
Redis replies Already Locked, Server B waits.

Step 3
Server A updates database.
Inventory
Payment
Order Status

Step 4
Server A releases lock, Unlock(Order101)

Step 5
Redis now gives lock to Server B, Perfect synchronization.


Evolution of Locks

No Lock
     ↓
Mutex / Monitor Lock
     ↓
Read-Write Lock
     ↓
Optimistic Lock
     ↓
Pessimistic Lock
     ↓
Database Lock
     ↓
Distributed Lock

Each lock solves a different problem.

1. No Lock
Imagine two threads updating the same bank account.

Balance = $100
Thread A withdraws $20
Thread B withdraws $30
Both read 100, and Both calculate independently.
100 - 20 = 80
100 - 30 = 70
Final balance becomes 70 but Expected 50
This is called Race Condition

2. Mutex Lock (Mutual Exclusion)
Purpose
Only one thread enters the critical section.

          Thread A
              |
          Gets Lock
              |
      Critical Section
              |
         Releases Lock
         
	   Thread B
        |
   Waiting

Java 
synchronized(lock) {
    updateBalance();
}
or
ReentrantLock
Works only
	• inside one JVM 
	• one machine 
Not across servers.

3. Read-Write Lock
Sometimes 100 users are only reading. Only one user writes.
Should readers wait? No.
Instead Readers
Thread A
Thread B
Thread C
Can run together.
--------------------
Writer
Thread D
Must wait
Example

Product Catalog
Thousands of users
↓

Reading products
↓

One admin updates price
Many readers.
Single writer.

Java - ReadWriteLock
Benefit - Much higher throughput.

4. Optimistic Lock
Assumption: Nobody will modify the data. Instead of locking, check later.
Example
Version = 10, Thread A reads

Version =10, Thread B reads

Version =10, Thread A updates

Version becomes 11 Thread B now tries then Database says
Expected Version=10
Actual Version=11

Update rejected. Retry. No locking. Very scalable.

Commonly implemented using @Version JPA Hibernate
Good for Mostly Reads, Rare Writes

5. Pessimistic Lock
Opposite assumption.
Assume conflicts will happen.
Lock first. Then update.

Thread A - Gets Lock - Updates Unlocks

Thread B - Waits

SQL
SELECT * FROM Account FOR UPDATE;
Nobody else can update.

Best for Banking, Payments, Inventory, Trade-off, Less concurrency.

6. Database Locks
Database itself manages locks.

Types
Row Lock
Table Lock
Page Lock
Schema Lock

Example

UPDATE Employee WHERE ID=100 Only Employee 100 gets locked.
Other rows remain available.
If ALTER TABLE Employee, Entire table may lock.

Row Lock
Employee Table
ID  Name
1   John
2   Alice
3   Bob
Can Only ID=2 locked. Highly scalable.


Comparison Table
Lock Type	Scope	Best For	Drawback
Mutex	Single Thread/Process	Critical section	One JVM only
Read-Write Lock	Single JVM	Read-heavy systems	Writer starvation possible
Optimistic Lock	Database/Application	Low conflict workloads	Retries on conflict
Pessimistic Lock	Database	High conflict workloads	Lower concurrency
Database Lock	Database	Row/Table protection	Database contention
Distributed Lock	Multiple Servers	Microservices, Distributed Systems	Network latency and lock management complexity

Interviewer: When would you use each type of lock?
Answer:
	• Mutex (synchronized, ReentrantLock) – Protect shared memory within a single JVM. 
	• Read-Write Lock – Use when reads are much more frequent than writes (e.g., product catalogs, configuration caches). 
	• Optimistic Lock – Use when conflicts are rare and you want maximum throughput (e.g., user profiles, order history). 
	• Pessimistic Lock – Use when conflicts are common and data consistency is critical (e.g., banking, payments, inventory deduction). 
	• Database Locks – Let the database enforce consistency for rows or tables during transactions. 
	• Distributed Lock – Use when multiple application instances across different servers must coordinate access to the same shared resource (e.g., cron jobs, inventory reservation, leader election).
